BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:vW7mutsRS1jJHMGswAm7D
SUMMARY:Boren Banner Series: Camille Trautman
DTSTAMP:20260402T030259Z
DTSTART:20260410T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Every photograph is a reminder that the act of framing is never
	 neutral. In Camille Trautman’s first solo museum exhibition in their home
	town\, the Seattle-born Duwamish artist uses photography and video to chal
	lenge colonial narratives and counter Indigenous erasure. The exhibition p
	resents selections from their ongoing series The North American LCD—spectr
	al self-portraits staged in varied natural landscapes. Rooted in Trautman’
	s process of coming out as transgender\, the images show the artist’s body
	 partially obscured by large LCD screens. The series examines how both lan
	dscape photography and digital media can shape or distort cultural identit
	y\, often by promoting or denying visibility.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.
	com/events/#/details/boren-banner-series-camille-trautman/16813305/2026-04
	-10T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/boren-banner-series-camil
	le-trautman/16813305/2026-04-10T00
LOCATION:Frye Art Museum\, 704 Terry Ave\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT6H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:iVsAb-hLZAmk4wctsnvrg
SUMMARY:Boren Banner Series: Camille Trautman
DTSTAMP:20260402T030259Z
DTSTART:20260410T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Every photograph is a reminder that the act of framing is never
	 neutral. In Camille Trautman’s first solo museum exhibition in their home
	town\, the Seattle-born Duwamish artist uses photography and video to chal
	lenge colonial narratives and counter Indigenous erasure. The exhibition p
	resents selections from their ongoing series The North American LCD—spectr
	al self-portraits staged in varied natural landscapes. Rooted in Trautman’
	s process of coming out as transgender\, the images show the artist’s body
	 partially obscured by large LCD screens. The series examines how both lan
	dscape photography and digital media can shape or distort cultural identit
	y\, often by promoting or denying visibility.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.
	com/events/#/details/boren-banner-series-camille-trautman/16813305/2026-04
	-10T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/boren-banner-series-camil
	le-trautman/16813305/2026-04-10T00
LOCATION:Frye Art Museum\, 704 Terry Ave\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-arts
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Arts & Culture
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT6H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:0-6S_uT0eLvaUtOBlibtz
SUMMARY:Forest Garden Land & Community Tending Days
DTSTAMP:20260402T030259Z
DTSTART:20260410T180000Z
DESCRIPTION:Help us grow this March during Forest Garden Land & Community T
	ending Days at the Daybreak Star Indian Cultural Center! 🌱✨ \n\nCome suppo
	rt Indigenous food sovereignty by tending to traditional plants like camas
	 and huckleberry. The plants grown here nourishes our elders\, youth\, fam
	ilies\, and ceremonies. Help us build a future rooted in culture\, care\, 
	and connection! 🍓 \n\nQuestions? Email Shameka.Gagnier@gmail.com or call/t
	ext \\(720\\) 212 7113 📞\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/
	forest-garden-land-community-tending-days/18443409/2026-04-10T00\n\nFrom S
	EAtoday - Community & Civic
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/forest-garden-land-commun
	ity-tending-days/18443409/2026-04-10T00
LOCATION:Daybreak Star Indian Cultural Center\, 5011 Bernie Whitebear Way\,
	 Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-community
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - Community & Civic
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT3H30M
END:VEVENT
